SIMPLE: rejoin
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rejoin
<hw>Re*join"</hw> <pr>(r?-join")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Rejoined</conjf>
<pr>(-joind")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rejoining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>rejoindre</ets>; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>joindre</ets> to join. See <er>Join</er>, and
cf. <er>Rejoinder</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To join again; to unite
after separation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To come, or go, again into the presence of; to join
the company of again.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Meet and <qex>rejoin</qex> me, in the pensive grot.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To state in reply; -- followed by an object
clause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rejoin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rejoin
<hw>Re*join"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To answer to a
reply.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To answer, as the defendant to the
plaintiff's replication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rejoinder</ent>⟦br⟧
